export const batch173 = {
  'the-plan-manage-your-time-like-a-lazy-genius.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-plan-manage-your-time-like-a-lazy-genius', title: 'The PLAN', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781637297666 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Trying to hold it all at once',
        text: "These days, culture moves at full tilt, and getting things done has quietly become a way of measuring worth. Nobody escapes the squeeze, but women absorb the heaviest dose of multitasking pressure. The yardstick is no longer just hitting work goals. It also demands magazine-cover polish in every corner of living. In real life, women juggle caregiver, organizer, and self-improvement project in the same breath, with absurd asks and almost zero payoff.\n\nThe same chorus keeps repeating. Dream big. Set goals. Have it all. As if existence were a cheap poster on a break room wall. That outlook works more like a hamster wheel to nowhere, locking everyone into endless motion. There is nonstop pressure to optimize and grind, as if missing one box on the list makes a person broken. That is where the hidden tax of the productivity race lives. The finish line never stops moving, and for women, it shifts faster than for anyone else.\n\nLoving what you love and going deep is not perfectionism. It is wholeness.\n\nEvery planner tossed out and every Monday vow to begin again points to the same fault line. It is time for something different. You deserve an approach that actually sees the chaos women navigate, between work demands, family turmoil, hormonal swings, and clock-short days. That is why this plan exists. Let us finally find something that actually delivers.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Why the setup fails you',
        text: "Before jumping into a fresh approach, here is something worth clearing up. You are not drowning in tasks because you are lazy or weak. Look a little closer and you will see the system prefers you stuck.\n\nSince the steam age, the push to do more and faster has shaped the work climate. Screens were meant to lighten the load, yet they doubled down on the old hustle ideals, producing a faster and less forgiving system.\n\nPassing off tasks is a smart way to manage your fuel and cut down on needless strain.\n\nThere is another wrinkle. The innocent hope of being a useful member of society has built a self-feeding machine. Sectors and the public feed each other to crank out more. As long as output stays a priority, the marketplace thrives, and the marketplace fuels more output. The loop feeds itself like a serpent eating its tail. It does not want you content. It needs you constantly chasing and wondering if you are doing enough.\n\nLet us be honest. The bar is not the same for everyone. Most men do not have to juggle a job, run a household, and raise kids. Half the time, no one even wonders if they want kids. Meanwhile, the productivity industry, mostly invented by men and aimed at men, sets the yardstick for what women's careers and lives should resemble.\n\nFind the nerve to love yourself in your messy glory and tune into what you really want.\n\nSpotting the cracks in the system is a clear first move toward a fresh path, one built by women, for women. Start by trading the dream of excellence in everything for the goal of integration. You are not a machine. You are a real, beautifully imperfect person who wants to enjoy life, keep it together most of the time, and feel a little more settled.\n\nHow often does the need to look in control and the pull of perfectionism show up in your day. Let go of fear, anxiety, and the sense of helplessness. The less they control you, the more whole you feel across every corner of yourself.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Plan with a calm, clear head',
        text: "If you want life to feel a bit more manageable, it is time to meet the PLAN: Prepare, Live, Adjust, and Notice. The acronym hands you four practical pieces of advice. The first two, Prepare and Live, are proactive and help you intentionally shape and experience your day. Begin with them, then move into the reactive steps, Adjust and Notice, which work well for handling curveballs.\n\nPrepare. Get your priorities in line. Preparation is not about stuffing every task into your day. It is about figuring out what matters right now. Start by naming what carries the most weight in your current moment. Whether it is steering a project, holding a tough conversation, or keeping your mornings easy, clarity on what matters helps you move forward with purpose.\n\nSmall shifts build lasting habits without the burnout of an all-or-nothing push.\n\nIf worry lingers even after you set priorities, focus on the messiest part. Find out what is really stressing you out and handle that first instead of trying to fix the whole picture at once.\n\nLife is a stack of seasons, usually several at once, and learning to be present inside them will change your life, as Kendra Adachi has written.\n\nLive. Focus on the season you are in. In this case, seasons are not winter, spring, summer, and autumn. You name them yourself, so make them specific, flexible, and as detailed as you want. Take parenting, for example. It can feel crushing when you picture it as one massive responsibility. When you split it into smaller pieces, it becomes far easier to approach.\n\nParenting is more than parenting. It is picking the right school, handling the first phone purchase, hunting for the right prom dress, and guiding a child through college forms. Yes, each step tests patience and grit, yet treating them as separate seasons makes them feel lighter. The smaller you make your season, the easier it is to focus and move forward without losing sight of what counts.\n\nFor context, the American Bar Association's latest report names 2016 to 2026 as the Decade of the Female Lawyer, noting the strong rise of women in legal work.",
      },
      {
        title: 'How you respond shapes the day',
        text: "When your boss schedules a last-minute call during lunch, your doctor appointment runs long, or your child has a poorly timed emergency, you have to pick priorities on the spot. In those moments it is time to shift from proactive to reactive mode, and the shift often comes with a side of stress and maybe a quick snack.\n\nAdjust. Value your fuel. When life feels chaotic, the temptation is to toss the planner and start over. In reality, small tweaks work far better than full resets. They let you respond to real needs without overloading your nervous system, since they take less mental effort. Starting small can feel too slow when you want fast results, but drastic change works like a harsh diet. Cut calories too severely and before long you find yourself dreaming about ice cream in the freezer. Cravings spiral and old patterns return.\n\nWhen you adjust, match your bar to your fuel. If fuel is low, lower the bar. It is not giving up. It is focusing on what truly counts. For instance, if late nights have worn you down, resist the urge to overhaul your routine overnight. Pick one thing to cut back on, like scrolling through social media. Do not make a sudden shift. Start small by setting a timer to limit your screen time. After a while, check in on how you feel and add another tweak if it feels right.\n\nTrust your gut when making calls. You know your needs and situation better than anyone.\n\nNotice. Observe and learn from it. Humans are natural observers, yet we often fixate on the wrong things, which leads to judgment, shame, or comparison. Noticing should be an act of kindness, especially toward yourself, your feelings, and your responses.\n\nGive yourself space to notice without rushing to react. Not everything needs fixing. Sometimes a mess is just a mess, and not every flaw is yours to resolve. Even in the chaos, the small good is still there, because you are still standing.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Begin with right now',
        text: "Some days you are ready to take on the world, and on others just surviving feels heroic. That is why you need two contrasting frameworks that intentionally end with yes. Whether you are bursting with fuel or barely scraping by, defining what matters and saying yes to it brings confidence and kindness to your choices.\n\nInstead of stressing about the big goal, focus on the steps you can take today to bring it closer.\n\nWhen you wake up buzzing with energy, channel that enthusiasm with the energetic TODAY. Tricky points to the day's challenges. Maybe it is overlapping meetings or shuttling kids around during rush hour. Use your extra fuel to untangle tricky problems before they grow. Optional reminds you that you do not have to do everything. Identify optional tasks and let them go if time runs short. Delightful asks you to pause and find joy in small things, like a favorite playlist, a cup of coffee, or a quick chat with a friend. Active asks what matters most today, whether finishing a work project or sticking to your cleaning routine. Channel your fuel toward what means the most to you. Yes, after reflecting on all the previous points, say yes to what resonates with your heart.\n\nLow-fuel days call for a different strategy rooted in kindness and realism. Try the gentle TODAY. Tender asks you to notice what feels hard right now and acknowledge it without judgment. Output asks you to be honest about what you can realistically do. Focus on the essentials and let the rest wait. Delegate means handing off tasks that do not need your direct touch. Share the load with a partner, coworker, or your future self. Accept means releasing the pressure to keep up your usual pace. Recognize that things may not go perfectly today, since imperfection is a natural part of life. Yes means saying yes to rest and quiet. This day will pass, and tomorrow is a chance to start fresh.\n\nFor reference, in 2023 women held over 35 percent of senior management roles worldwide. According to the Grant Thornton International Business Report, it was the highest figure yet and a promising step toward closing the gender gap in leadership.",
      },
      {
        title: 'The four seasons of the cycle',
        text: "Women's time and fuel are closely tied to hormonal rhythms, yet society often overlooks the link. That is not surprising, since women's hormonal changes have historically been misunderstood and misrepresented. Hippocrates, often called the Father of Medicine, famously claimed that a woman's uterus could move around her body and cause discomfort and erratic behavior, a condition many simply called hysteria.\n\nDo not judge every day by your best day. Some days are for thriving, others for surviving, and both are valid.\n\nMedicine has come a long way since then, but women's health is still catching up in research and support. There is a way to reclaim control without waiting for systemic change, by aligning your life with your cycle so each phase mirrors a season. The menstrual phase covers days 1 to 5 and is your winter, a time to retreat and restore. Fuel is low, so lean into tasks that do not demand much output, like paying bills or meal prepping. If even that feels too much, give yourself permission to rest and avoid emotional overexertion. The follicular phase covers days 6 to 12. As fuel builds, this spring-like phase brings curiosity. Use it to strategize, organize, and start new projects. Whether you are planning a trip, refreshing your wardrobe, or diving into creative work, this is an ideal window to prepare for what is ahead. The ovulation phase covers days 13 to 18. Like summer, it is a brief and vibrant phase when confidence peaks. You are naturally more outgoing and self-assured. Schedule social events and important meetings during this window. Embrace it to live in your strength and connect with others. The luteal phase runs from day 19 to the start of your period. Autumn brings grounded fuel, ideal for detailed tasks or evaluating systems that need tweaking. Clean, organize, and tie up loose ends. It is also a time to reflect on the month and prepare for the next cycle.\n\nYou cannot live well if you do not pay attention to where you are right now, as Kendra Adachi has written.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thought',
        text: "Life does not demand perfection. It asks for presence. Plans fail, goals stretch further than expected, and sometimes everything feels like too much. That is not a sign of personal failure. It is a beautifully chaotic life. Change is constant, and so is your capacity to adapt. Let each step be enough, and trust that living with intention today builds the foundation for harmony and fulfillment. Take a breath and be kind to yourself.\n\nTry this. Rename how you see a problem. Turn \"I am bad at mornings\" into \"I am figuring out my mornings.\" Create a meal rotation by choosing five easy recipes and repeating them weekly to avoid decision fatigue. Set reminders for recurring tasks like grocery shopping or bills to prevent oversights and cut stress. Check out Happier with Gretchen Rubin and The Lazy Genius Podcast for tips that make daily life easier.\n\nRead it till the end.",
      },
    ],
  },
  'the-procrastination-equation.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-procrastination-equation', title: 'The Procrastination Equation', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781636405800 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Knowing the root of stalling helps you handle it',
        text: "Most of us have wrestled with putting things off at some point. Yet we tend to write it off as a lapse in judgment instead of digging into why we do it in the first place. In the chapters ahead, you will see why this habit wrecks your life and how to climb out of that hole.\n\nPutting things off is often confused with laziness, yet a staller is different. A lazy person never gets things done. A staller eventually does the task, but only after a long fight.\n\nPositive qualities like prudence, patience, and prioritizing share one thing with stalling. They all involve delay. Yet they are not the same as putting things off. Stalling is far more than pushing tasks to a later time. It is irrationally postponing work even when you know it could harm you.\n\nWhen we face the fallout of stalling, we promise ourselves it will never happen again. The problem with that promise is that it fails to treat the habit as something ingrained. So we fall into self-deception because we cannot wish the behavior away or, worse, justify it away.\n\nResearch shows that impulsiveness sits at the heart of stalling.\n\nOur craving to live in the now pushes us to put off what we should be doing. The craving cuts across every field of human effort and is slightly stronger in men than women.\n\nFor those of us who are less impulsive, worry often acts as an internal cue that gets us started on a project early. For those who are more impulsive, the story is different. Worry over a deadline leads straight to stalling, as Piers Steel has written.\n\nWhen a person is impulsive, they avoid any task that brings worry. Even if they start, they get pulled away by something else in no time.\n\nShould you be doing something yet cannot find the motivation to start. This summary will help you understand what stalling is and what to do about it. You will see the formula and learn how to apply it.\n\nFor context, the word procrastination first showed up in English in the 16th century.",
      },
      {
        title: 'The formula: expectancy times value, divided by impulsiveness times delay',
        text: "The formula has four parts: Expectancy, Value, Impulsiveness, and Delay.\n\nExpectancy is the confidence you have in your ability to create the thing you are trying to create. Value describes the meaning you attach to the work. Impulsiveness covers the things likely to pull you away from doing the task. Delay deals with how close the deadline sits. The further away the deadline, the less likely you are to do the task.\n\nThese factors decide whether we stall or not, and they stand apart from the strongest social science theories of motivation. We tend to delay tasks that are not urgent, and that growing delay drains our motivation. When impulsiveness combines with this fuzzy sense of how much time we actually have, stalling becomes inevitable. The only counterweight is the value we place on the task and our confidence in the payoff. For example, if you promise a child video games after finishing their chores, they will speed through the chores, but only if they value the games and trust that you will keep your word. They are less likely to get pulled away and they will not delay, because they know finishing fast means more play time.\n\nTo curb stalling, we have to push expectancy and value up while pulling impulsiveness and delay down.\n\nFor every task, ask yourself these questions. How sure am I that I can pull it off. That is Expectancy. Does this work have real meaning to me. That is Value. How likely am I to be pulled away by instant gratification. That is Impulsiveness. How long will this project take to finish. That is Delay.\n\nAnswering these questions reveals the strategies you need to put in place to finish on time. It also helps you see whether this is a task you should be doing at all.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Building a success spiral to raise your confidence',
        text: "A success spiral is a strategy that helps maximize motivation toward a goal. It works by breaking the main goal into challenging but achievable milestones. As you cross each milestone, you build the momentum you need to reach the next one until the whole goal is done. Each milestone must feel meaningful and show you what you are capable of. Polynesian explorers colonized the South Pacific using spirals. When they spotted a new island from their home port, they made it their next achievable goal. They focused on reaching it and built plans to get there. After settling it, they turned their attention to the next island and made it their new target.\n\nEach win propels us toward the next win.\n\nTo raise expectancy, we need to create success spirals. It does not have to be a new island in the South Pacific. It can be as simple as finishing your first task of the day. Making your bed in the morning, for example, can propel you to get more done. If you do not believe you can pull something off, you may not want to spend the energy trying. And if you have not finished something recently, how do you know you can pull off a new goal. You do not have any momentum.\n\nThe opposite of the success spiral is the downward spiral. Stalling can pull you into it. You keep piling up unfinished projects and lose faith in your ability to finish new ones. The good news is that the ability to spiral down also means you can spiral up. Think of dominoes. Knocking over the first domino uses the power of compounding to knock down the next ones, and you only need to focus on that first domino.\n\nPlan your day the night before. Decide what you will finish first the next day. Begin your day by doing something meaningful before other activities crowd in. Make a checklist and cross items off as you finish them. Reminding yourself of your wins helps you build momentum.\n\nA good day eventually spirals up into a good life.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Raising the worth of a task through mental contrasting',
        text: "Visualization needs mental contrasting to help you beat stalling in a useful way. When you paint mental pictures of where you want to be, you have to compare them with where you are now, and that comparison adds worth to your goals. Creating visuals of a goal without this second step drains motivational fuel.\n\nMental contrasting does not create optimism, but it maximizes the motivational benefits of optimism, creating energy, effort, and a jumpstart in planning, as Piers Steel has written.\n\nIf you have been practicing creative visualization, you do not have to stop. You only need to add a picture of where you are right now. The following steps help. Fix an image of the life you want in your mind. Pick one aspect of that life and focus on it. Articulate why this piece of your future life is attractive to you. Mentally contrast that life with where you are at the moment. Vividly describe the gap between your current life and your visualized life.\n\nTaking these steps will motivate you to pursue the ideal life you have painted.\n\nValue is a key part of the formula.\n\nRaising the value or expected value of what you want helps you find the strength to act now.\n\nThe acronym WOOP describes a practice that combines the vision of a compelling future with reality so that the precise action becomes clear. WOOP stands for Wish, Outcome, Obstacles, and Plan. Wish asks what important wish you want to pull off. Outcome asks what the best result would be from achieving that wish. Obstacles asks what the main obstacle is in reaching this goal. Plan asks what is an effective action to tackle that obstacle.\n\nWish is the first step and is like visualization. Outcome is the second step and describes the value of the wish. Obstacles focuses on the gap between your reality and the wish. Plan names the practical steps you will take when the obstacles show up.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Cutting distractions gives you an extra month each year',
        text: "Distractions are everywhere and they take more than they give. Removing them lets you focus on one task and see it through. For example, turning off audio notifications in your email settings raises efficiency by 10 percent, according to Piers Steel. Over a year, that adds up to one extra month.\n\nCheck your email at a set time rather than every time you hear the beep.\n\nDo not underestimate the role distraction plays in getting things done. It takes extra time to get back into full focus after a break. And every time you allow yourself to be pulled away from work, you have to summon the strength to resume.\n\nThis practice helps you cut impulsiveness. Yet it is not enough to raise expectation and value. You also have to pull impulsiveness and delay down.\n\nWhile cutting distractions is a key step toward lowering impulsiveness, it is often hard to disable every notification on your devices. Put your phone on airplane mode and in another room when you are doing your best work, and shut down browser extensions that pull you to distracting sites. You will be tempted to stop doing this, and it is important to push through those temptations.\n\nStep into flow and become ten times more productive. Flow is a mental state where you can get ten times the amount of work done in the same span of time. You can create and recreate the flow state if you set up your environment correctly. Beyond removing distractions, pick a specific goal and a specific time frame during which you will work without interruptions. Use focusing music to boost concentration on the work in front of you.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Skimping on sleep fuels stalling because you are too tired to work',
        text: "Sleep matters because it makes nearly everything better. We set alarms to wake up, yet sometimes we need to set alarms to go to sleep, since eight hours of sleep each night improves productivity during the day. Plenty of sleep boosts cognitive performance, so tasks stop feeling cumbersome.\n\nTiredness sits at the top of the list of reasons people put things off. Sleep helps beat tiredness.\n\nSet up a sleep routine. Pick a specific time when you need to be in bed and build a pre-bed ritual that calms your nervous system, like drinking tea, reading a book, or meditating. Going straight from work to bed can make it hard to fall asleep. Also, create a good sleep environment by turning off the lights, using dark curtains, or playing slow music.\n\nGoal setting, the kind that is done properly, is the smartest move you can make to fight stalling, as Piers Steel has written.\n\nWhenever we are stressed, we lose willpower, and when willpower wanes, we give in to impulses instead of steering them. So we end up doing things we should not and putting off the ones we should. We have to recognize that there is a limit to the fuel we have in a day. That recognition lets us budget the fuel we have and refuel when needed. For example, a dieter should not wait until they are starving before eating, or they will fall for the carbs and fats all around them. Similarly, to fight stalling, use your moments of strength to remove the things that easily distract or drain you.\n\nStudy yourself to know whether you are sharpest early in the morning or a night owl. Schedule your most important tasks a few hours after you wake up, since that is when you are likely to be most efficient. A short nap during the day can extend your efficient phase. If you cannot nap, take a walk at lunchtime.\n\nFor reference, the liver metabolizes alcohol best about 12 hours after we wake up.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thought',
        text: "Set challenging and meaningful goals to maximize motivation and beat stalling by using the strategies shared here. Set your goals right after this closing, so you do not put off applying the solutions.\n\nBe as specific as you can when setting goals and pick an actual deadline. If the goal is long-term, apply positive spirals by breaking it into smaller milestones. If a goal feels hard to reach, find a portion of it you can tackle. Reaching that milestone helps you cut the tendency to delay. For example, you could decide to write a single page of a book you have been putting off. Writing that page may be all the momentum you need to write a whole chapter. And writing a chapter may propel you to write more chapters.\n\nCreate a routine around your goals and stick to the schedule. Pick a time when you do that specific task and a place to do it.\n\nThe formula demands that we raise expectation and value while lowering impulsiveness and delay. So make your goals specific and time-based by creating a plan with actionable steps. Then name the daily activities you must do to follow your plan.\n\nFinally, since screens are the number one way we stall, we need to band together to build self-control into these devices. For example, if these devices recorded and reported our activities, we might be able to curb the excesses. What we measure can be improved. So stalling can be defeated if we all band together to insist on controlling our devices rather than letting them control us.\n\nTry this. Whatever you are putting off, take the following steps. Write down what you want to finish and when, and be specific. Break the goal into short-term milestones or objectives. Create daily activities you have to do to reach the milestones.\n\nRead it till the end.",
      },
    ],
  },
  'the-promise-of-a-pencil.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-promise-of-a-pencil', title: 'The Promise of a Pencil', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781607410056 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'You share a stake in getting underprivileged kids into school',
        text: "It does not matter whether you are a donor or you are actively involved with a nonprofit or an NGO. Whether you give a single coin or a six-figure check. One thing worth knowing is that it matters to find a way to help children from many poor countries get to school.\n\nEducation is the roadmap to a successful life, and every child has a right to a full life.\n\nThere is no amount too small or too big to give, because you are actively contributing to the development of society.\n\nAs long as you can dream it, you can achieve it, and that is what Adam Braun talks about in this book. There is no place too small to find inspiration, and as long as you are dedicated to reaching your goals, you can make a difference.\n\nAn item as small as a pencil can be deeply symbolic, because some children around the world cannot even afford one. The promise of a pencil can go a long way in shaping the life of a child and many others, as this summary explains. You can always help people, and if you are looking for ways to start and how to go about it, this summary comes highly recommended.\n\nRead it till the end.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Turning that first spark into real steps is essential for success',
        text: "Ervin Braun, Adam Braun's father, was an intimidating man who expected his children to give their best effort no matter the circumstances. Adam and his siblings, a brother and a sister, were to follow their father's rules at all times. Their father's preferences guided their movements, and they dared not disappoint him. That upbringing taught Adam a great deal, and he understood that, strict as his father was, he was only trying to enforce discipline.\n\nErvin Braun understood the value of education, which is why he wanted his children to be the best versions of themselves. It is this belief that carried Adam Braun across the world.\n\nThe value of education cannot be overstated, because it is the lens through which the world can be seen.\n\nEducation is not limited to the four walls of a classroom. Although Adam played basketball in high school and dreamed of going pro, he changed his mind. In his sophomore year of college, he decided to go on a spiritual quest. He signed up with a group of travelers on an educational program and began his trip across the world on a ship. The ship ran into trouble at sea, taking on serious damage. Adam prayed and felt a spiritual presence inside him that assured him he would survive.\n\nA sense of the spiritual can give you extra motivation if you believe it is there.\n\nIn every country they visited, Adam asked children what they would want most if they could have anything in the world. The children gave all sorts of answers, but Adam was struck by a boy who said he wanted a pencil. He gave the boy a pencil and concluded that every pencil carries a purpose. To that boy, a pencil was all he needed to pursue what he really wanted. The pencil stood for a way to get an education, and this deepened Adam's belief that every child deserves quality schooling.\n\nRead it till the end.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Building a quality, sustainable education system is a shared responsibility',
        text: "Adam Braun came up with the idea to start a nonprofit that provides basic quality schooling at the primary level for children from poor or developing countries. He named the organization Pencils of Promise, or PoP. In his first three months, Adam raised more than $35,000 in donations.\n\nHis first school, set up in Pha Theung in Laos, was a huge success. Almost the whole village turned up for the groundbreaking ceremony. The people were thrilled to finally have a school, giving Adam indescribable joy.\n\nSchooling is central to the growth of any society. Without it, ignorance takes over and leads to regression and stagnation.\n\nUsing social media, Adam launched a platform where people could see his work and read his mission statements. He partnered with strong brands and discovered that people were ready to help when it came to raising money for schooling. He also mentored young people and gave them a reason to advocate for education for children in deprived areas.\n\nAdam believes schooling plays a defining role in a child's life and in the kind of adult that child will become. As he continued to build schools, he received a great deal of help from people and whole communities. Some pledged manual labor, while others gave monetary donations or land.\n\nSetting up a learning facility is a shared responsibility, both within and outside a community. The benefits of a strong educational system are not limited to one person. They serve the general interest of the whole society.\n\nAdam's organization gained wider exposure when he met his brother's friend. The friend, Justin Bieber, was a budding musician whose fan base was growing every day. Bieber became a committed member of PoP and used his youthful popularity to spread its message to more people around the world.\n\nSchooling opens the mind to many things and widens your horizon beyond what sits in front of you. There is no limit to what you can achieve as long as you are dedicated to it. Small steps grow into big projects when the cause is just.",
      },
      {
        title: 'A realized goal is only real when a plan turns the idea into action',
        text: "Adam Braun made a plan to officially launch the PoP story in the media and show people what they were about. To do that, he needed to expand and give the organization a serious look.\n\nWhen priorities clash in those moments, stay guided by your values, not by what feels urgent, as Adam Braun has written.\n\nAlmost two years after launch, he hired paid staff and moved to a bigger office. He brought in stronger professionals and set up a team of strong volunteers. Adam built his big announcements on three main frameworks. The amazing story framework aimed to create a moment where people's first reaction to seeing the mission statement would be awe mixed with a small pang of regret, since they would be annoyed at themselves for not hearing about PoP sooner. He wanted a story so compelling that people would be eager to be part of the projects. The online presence framework gave people a chance to watch the organization's progress and offer feedback. This would let the organization know how people reacted and welcome their suggestions and ideas. Adam saw the online presence as a key factor for funds, donations, and referrals. The professional organization framework was based on the idea that people's perception of an organization rests on its professional look and reliability. With a bigger space and more staff, PoP could take on bigger projects and partner with stronger brands.\n\nA plan on its own is not enough to start a project. You have to take concrete steps that convince people to buy into your ideas.\n\nPoP received nationwide recognition when HuffPost ran a cover story on its mission and intentions. Many organizations and news outlets requested interviews and a chance to support the organization's growth. Major TV networks aired those interviews, giving PoP a wider audience. Justin Bieber also donated a substantial amount of money, which let Adam and his team build more schools.",
      },
      {
        title: 'A successful organization builds happiness, friendship, reward, improvement, and fun',
        text: "Adam Braun's journey with PoP gave him the idea for the five personalities that defined his organization. These personalities became the principles of the organization.\n\nAny organization that wants to build a healthy and sustainable work environment should adopt these five principles: Happiness, Friendship, Reward, Improvement, and Fun.\n\nWhen your employees are happy coming to work, you have built an environment where productivity will always rise.\n\nWhen people feel satisfied with what they do, they are bonded by the success of a well-executed project. Helping children from poor countries get basic quality schooling is bound to spark happiness and create a friendship bond. Braun set up organizational events such as meditation breaks and jukebox sessions, where employees take turns playing their favorite songs.\n\nAs a way to appreciate donors and supporters, Adam also introduced a Closing the Loop program. This program assembles videos, audio, and pictures into a documentary that says thank you to donors and supporters and shows them what their contributions have achieved. It acts as a reward system, so donors and supporters feel they are part of something big and meaningful.\n\nIn moments of uncertainty, immerse yourself in the life you would be most proud to live, as Adam Braun has written.\n\nUsing feedback, Adam also created a way for people to share suggestions through a Launch and Learn program. This program fueled the organization's growth as people came in with useful ideas. He also borrowed from his father's principles about giving your best effort. Every employee at PoP knew they had to be at their best all the time. Volunteers who were not contributing were phased out, and more people were brought in to become active contributors.\n\nAn organization's success rests on the ability to improve by learning and reacting.\n\nFinally, Adam made sure people had fun working with him and the organization. People were free to contribute and share ideas, and he built his organization on a foundation of friendliness and service.",
      },
      {
        title: 'It is fine to be scared by the size of a project, but never let that scare stop you',
        text: "As the years went by, PoP grew bigger and stronger, which meant Adam had to expand. The size of the projects ahead of him was intimidating, but instead of giving up, he decided to press onward.\n\nFirst, he met with Ray Chambers, a renowned philanthropist with years of experience. Chambers was interested in his ideas and joined the board. He taught Braun the value of spirituality in relation to service and urged him not to overlook the spiritual side of his work.\n\nSecond, Braun enrolled in a program at Harvard on Exponential Fundraising. The program taught him how to ask for donations without feeling awkward and how to convince donors to part with large sums of money. When he met Paul Foster, an investment banker, Braun put his training to work and asked for a six-figure donation. To his delight, he got it, along with a useful piece of advice. Foster told him that if he wanted to collect large sums, he had to look the part, dress the part, and be convincing. He also told Braun to follow up by constantly sharing what he did with the money. The advice paid off, and he was able to raise a great deal of money for the organization.\n\nThe first step to tackling a problem is to build a conviction inside yourself that you will find a way around it.\n\nYou must never be put off by a project simply because you think it is too big. It is never too late to admit that you need more knowledge. Go ahead and gain it, because no one has a monopoly on knowledge.\n\nAdam's PoP organization had built over 200 schools by 2014, with plans to build at least 300 more. The team had also hired more people and was planning to train over a thousand teachers worldwide.\n\nTo give more to the community, they set up a scholarship program aimed at supporting at least 10,000 students by the end of 2015. The scale of these plans shows how far a single step and the determination to succeed can take you.\n\nFor context, according to United Institute of Statistics data, almost 60 percent of youth between the ages of about 15 and 17 in Africa are not in school.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thought',
        text: "The decisions you make can shape the lives of people who live thousands of miles away. Your dreams are valid as long as you are determined to see them through. Living your dream requires sacrifice and a commitment to learn and unlearn many things. You cannot know it all, which is why you have to stay open-minded.\n\nAdam Braun's decision came from the inspiration he found in a child who needed a pencil. This shows that little things inspire some of the biggest dreams. You do not have to wait for a big break before you start achieving your goals. Small steps will take you to greater heights if you stay focused and dedicated. The best thing you can do for yourself is believe in yourself. Self-belief gives you the confidence to navigate storms and come out on top.\n\nEducation is essential and mandatory. It is the vehicle that carries you across the world from where you stand. It lets you travel across miles without leaving the spot where you are. Schooling gives you more significant opportunities and helps you expand beyond what is in front of you. You are never too small or too old to dream of doing something great. Like Adam Braun, you can draw inspiration from small things around you, develop your immediate environment, and affect the wider world.\n\nTry this. Meet a child today and share the value of education. Do what you can to raise funds for the less privileged around you so they can get a quality education.\n\nRead it till the end.",
      },
    ],
  },
  'the-religions-book1.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-religions-book1', title: 'The Religions Book', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781608509309 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Faith gives people a way to make sense of the world',
        text: "Faith runs through the entire thread of human history. As far back as our cave-dwelling ancestors, we find traces of a belief system, from drawings on cave walls to early accounts of burial ceremonies. Two subjects pull humans toward faith: the wish for life after death and the wish to make sense of the world.\n\nFrom unexplained weather events to the question of how we came to live on this planet, faith has offered comfort to millions of people for centuries. We have pieced together the customs and ceremonies of past civilizations from relics uncovered in excavations, which gives a fascinating glimpse into history. In many faiths, the central tenets have not changed much since their beginnings. Life has evolved, yet the basics have stayed largely in place.\n\nEvery faith believes something slightly different from the others, yet the basics are often very similar in structure.\n\nFaith and morality are tightly bound. It is the broad idea of good versus evil, and the view that being and doing good is the path to heaven or a successful afterlife. With that in mind, many faiths guide followers toward a life that supports that aim. Morality differs from faith to faith, but every major faith has a strong focus on the afterlife.\n\nLearning more about the main faiths around the world helps knock down walls of confusion and helps everyone become more open-minded and accepting of one another. It is also genuinely interesting to learn more about traditions you may not know well, which makes this summary an enlightening read on many levels.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Ancient faith still shapes the major traditions of today',
        text: "We tend to think about the main faiths we still see today, like Christianity, Buddhism, Hinduism, Islam, and Judaism. Yet many civilizations across ancient history had their own belief systems. Those systems helped shape societies in particular regions, such as Egypt, and connect with the major traditions we see now.\n\nWe have established that the afterlife runs through every faith like a strong thread. The Ancient Egyptians may be the most famous example of elaborate rituals to ensure passage to the afterlife. Bowing down to Osiris, Lord of the Afterlife, ancient Egyptians often made considerable offerings to the dead, including building the Great Pyramids and a series of tombs underneath. Even the rituals we read about, such as mummifying and embalming, were all to ensure safe passage to the afterlife, or Aaru.\n\nEgyptians wanted to live after death as perfected beings in Aaru, the field of reeds, which was a perfected version of the Egypt they already knew, as Neil Philip has written.\n\nAnother historical figure who helped shape the idea of faith and passage into the afterlife was Confucius. A Chinese scholar, Confucius explored whether being a good person helped you pass into the afterlife, or whether goodness was something you were born with.\n\nFor acceptance into the afterlife, a person should focus on doing good throughout life. It should be for no benefit of their own, but simply because they can.\n\nConfucius' idea of morality held that a person could learn to be good to ensure acceptance into the afterlife. This includes doing good deeds for others, reading and learning for no reason other than to do it, and focusing on achieving something called ren, or humaneness. Confucius taught that someone who could do these things would secure acceptance into heaven.\n\nFor reference, the Ancient Egyptians believed that every person had a shadow that helped protect them and allowed them to make good choices throughout life.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Hindus hold many gods yet focus on a virtuous life',
        text: "Hinduism can be traced back to around 1700 BCE and is built on the Four Vedas, the oldest scriptures of the tradition, written in Sanskrit. The religion grounds itself in tradition, and despite its status as a religion, it does not follow the usual rules of one. For example, Hindus do not have a single deity or god.\n\nHinduism can feel confusing because it covers many slightly different traditions that span across India. Many customs vary from place to place, yet the basic way people live their lives stays the same.\n\nThe word Hindu roughly translates to Indian, which, compared to other faiths, makes Hinduism more of a way of life than a traditional belief system.\n\nEven without a named deity or prophet, Hindus follow the theory of samsara, the life cycle of birth, death, and rebirth of the soul, called atman. There is also a strong desire to attain moksha, which is release from the endless cycle of life and death, and progression to the afterlife.\n\nAs with most other traditions, to be admitted to the afterlife, you must conduct yourself in a certain way during life. Hindus call this dharma, which means living in the right way, being virtuous and appropriate. Those are loose terms and could be open to many interpretations. That is perhaps why some Hindus live in a much stricter way than others.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Buddha’s teachings led to the Buddhist tradition',
        text: "An interesting fact about Buddhism is that it did not become a religion until many years after Buddha's death. Buddha's teachings were passed down through his scholars, eventually leading followers to live their lives in pursuit of the same level of enlightenment.\n\nMeditation is considered a strong tool to help Buddhists reach spiritual awakening and enlightenment.\n\nAlthough Buddhism has a central figure to focus on, it is similar to Hinduism and tends to be more philosophical than some other established traditions, with variations spread across the Asian region. Buddha's teachings are also interesting because they were not built on a vision or message from outside but were drawn from his own experiences.\n\nMany years after Buddha passed away, his teachings, recorded in the Tipitaka, explained how to reach a state of enlightenment and see the path toward nirvana. At that point, you are above typical human desires and attachments, two things Buddha believed blocked human happiness and satisfaction. From this, the Four Noble Truths were founded. Dukkha is the main focus of suffering. Samudaya is the cause of suffering. Nirodha is the truth of the end of suffering. Magga is the truth of the path to ending suffering.\n\nBy achieving Magga, a difficult task, followers are on their way to the Middle Way, the same path Buddha followed to total enlightenment.\n\nNirvana is the ultimate goal for every Buddhist, reaching spiritual enlightenment at its highest level.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Jews have been persecuted for years yet hold firmly to their beliefs',
        text: "The first thing that comes to mind for many when they think of Judaism is the Holocaust. Yet that is not the only persecution Jewish people have faced. The Jewish tradition may be the oldest and most misunderstood of all religions, dating back to around 2000 BCE.\n\nThe Hebrew Bible, often called the Torah, describes God creating the world and His connection with the Jewish people in the Canaan region. God made a promise to the prophet Abraham that He would protect the Jewish people. He said that if they obeyed Him and His wishes, including circumcision to show their obedience, He would defend those who prayed and grant them Israel.\n\nThe unique agreement the Jews hold with God gives comfort to followers every day and helps them feel protected against hostile forces.\n\nThe Torah is so revered that nobody is allowed to touch it. It is kept in a safe spot within the synagogue and read using a pointer.\n\nThere is a great deal of misunderstanding around the Jewish faith, and this has led to many persecutions over the centuries. By learning more about this ancient tradition, we can help make sure history does not repeat itself in those horrific ways. The Jewish faith has a clear base in Israel, yet the historical horrors of past centuries have led many Jews to be displaced to other regions.\n\nLargely because of their position as displaced immigrants and their distinctive tradition, Jews have been widely persecuted throughout their history, as Neil Philip has written.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Christianity remains one of the most prevalent religions worldwide',
        text: "Christianity dates back to around the 1st century BCE. Christians believe in one God and in the Messiah, Jesus, who died on the cross and was resurrected to heaven, bringing salvation to humankind through His sacrifice.\n\nIn the Bible, Jesus is the Son of God in human form, and when He came to earth, it marked the start of the New Testament. Most of the Christian faith is built on the teachings of Jesus throughout the Gospels and places strong emphasis on the importance of living a good life in order to be admitted to heaven.\n\nPerhaps the most important story in the Bible is the crucifixion and Jesus' resurrection to heaven to be seated alongside God. The most important part of this story also refers to the Trinity. God exists in three ways: the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit.\n\nThe Roman Catholic religion is a branch of Christianity. Catholics are Christians. The other two branches of Christianity include Protestant and Orthodox. Within those, you also find different sub-branches, usually by country.\n\nCatholic followers are Christian, but not all Christians are Catholic.\n\nOne difference between Christianity and many other religions is that Jesus is considered to be more than a prophet. In many other religions, Jesus is not seen as the son of God.\n\nChristianity has helped shape a great deal of western culture, even though it began in Roman Judea.",
      },
      {
        title: 'The teachings of God as revealed in the Qur’an',
        text: "Islam is an ancient religion founded in 610 CE. Like several other world faiths, it is highly misunderstood. Muslims live their lives focused on doing good for others and committing themselves to God.\n\nOne reason Islam is so misunderstood is that many have taken the original teachings and twisted them into something far removed from what is actually contained within the Qur'an, the Islamic holy book. To better understand Islam, we need to set aside those preconceived notions and get back to basics, understanding the reality of daily life as a Muslim.\n\nWhat we see reported in the newspapers about Islam often misses the mark. It is essential to truly understand the religion and show respect to its followers.\n\nMuslims believe that the Prophet Muhammad received the revelations directly from God to be recorded in the Qur'an. This is considered the true message from Allah, or God, and was written in Arabic.\n\nIslam teaches belief in one God, and Muslims dedicate their lives to serving Allah. Life is considered a gift from God and should be lived in the right way, avoiding sin and temptation. On the Day of Judgement, it is how a person lived their life that determines whether they will go to heaven or hell.\n\nThe holiest city in Islam is Mecca, in Saudi Arabia, the birthplace of the Prophet Muhammad. Many Muslims spend their days in and around the local community mosque there. The Five Pillars of Islam are Shahada, the profession of faith. Salat is prayer. Zakat is almsgiving or offering worship to Allah. Sawm is fasting. Hajj is a pilgrimage to Mecca to be closer to Allah.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thought',
        text: "No religion is better or more important than another. All religions are equal. That is something we all need to understand from the start. What one person chooses to believe and how they choose to live their life is their personal choice. We should respect individual choices and learn to live side by side in harmony.\n\nThat would be a perfect world, would it not.\n\nUnfortunately, religion has caused divisions throughout history and even continues to do so in the modern world. The key to breaking down those walls is to understand religions and their true nature. When you only see small snapshots of what a religion is supposed to be about, it is easy to form a quick opinion. Yet it is vital to learn more and understand the facts.\n\nIslam is one of the most misunderstood religions, alongside Judaism. Yet there are countless myths and false rumors about all the others too. Religion remains a dividing subject, even though it is designed to bring people together. If we want to live in a harmonious world, we need to understand that the religion a person chooses and how they decide to live their lives is what brings them comfort and reassurance in this challenging world we live in. It is nobody else's business to judge or pass an opinion.\n\nOf course, religion as a subject is fascinating too. Perhaps by reading about different religions, you may decide to dig a little deeper and learn even more. Religion is not for everyone, but it is often most crucial for those who choose to live a religious life.\n\nTry this. If you want to learn more about a religion that a friend or colleague follows, it is fine to ask questions as long as you do it respectfully. Ask if they mind and then have a deep conversation to learn even more. Cast aside any preconceived ideas you may have about a particular religion and see it for what it is, a personal choice that someone has made to live their life a certain way. Explore your own ideas and thoughts on religion and see if they have changed after spending time with this summary.\n\nRead it till the end.",
      },
    ],
  },
  'the-road-to-character.json': {
    base: { id: 'the-road-to-character', title: 'The Road to Character', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781608595680 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Two pillars of a meaningful life',
        text: "As Rabbi Joseph explains in Lonely Man of Faith, we are made up of Adam I and Adam II. Adam I represents the factors that drive our external success, such as our skills and knowledge. Adam II defines our inner self, which covers how kind, brave, or weak we are.\n\nWe spend most of our lives building Adam I because we believe it matters more to our existence. We diligently master skills and chase major social victories, like a successful career and public recognition. Yet our life is not only a pursuit of success. It is also about believing in the good, belonging to something greater, and humbly adapting to unexpected change. Our existence is a blend of both virtues and self-awareness.\n\nOur identity and actions are two distinct aspects of our being, and aligning them is fundamental to building good character.\n\nTo find our way to our true selves, we have to pay attention to what really matters. Our lives should not revolve around enjoying the gifts of the earth alone. We have to be willing to share the goodness inside us with the world.\n\nThere is joy in a life filled with interdependence with others, in a life filled with gratitude, reverence, and admiration, as David Brooks has written.\n\nDrawing on his deep knowledge of history and statistical analysis, David Brooks offers valuable insights into common pitfalls and gives guidance on how to fix them. If you want to improve your character and redefine what life means to you, this summary will help.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Why humility carries such weight',
        text: "In the earlier days of figures like George W. Bush, humility was well-practiced and adopted as a way of life. Throughout his presidential campaign, Bush avoided excessive use of the word \"I\" because he believed it led to undue self-praise. Things have changed, and there has been a cultural shift away from humility and toward ego.\n\nWhen World War II ended in 1945, a special team took to the radio to spread humility. They accepted that their victory was not because they were better but because they were brave. In those days, the prevailing mindset was that, even though they took pride in their accomplishments, they did not consider themselves superior to others. That mentality stands in stark contrast with our contemporary world. A football player, for example, who makes a two-yard block on the pitch will roar in self-praise, beating his chest to say he is the best. We are more concerned about showing off than embracing humility today.\n\nThe quest for fame drives most of our everyday actions. When researchers asked a group of teenage girls if they would rather be Justin Bieber's personal assistant or the President of Harvard, 80 percent chose the first option. We have become obsessed with the paparazzi and the glamor of fame, often overlooking the bigger picture and seeing humility as a sign of weakness.\n\nThe more we focus on ourselves and how other people see us, the more self-centered we can become. While narcissism may look bold on the outside, it often reveals that ego-driven people are fragile and conflicted within. In contrast, humble people tend to be more confident, because they see an extraordinary situation as ordinary.\n\nHumility leads to wisdom. It gives us the freedom to open ourselves to learning, because we understand that we do not know everything.\n\nThere is no harm in having faith in our abilities. Confidence is a virtue. Yet excessive confidence can become a stumbling block. Instead, we should cultivate self-respect, which means recognizing our strengths while staying humble and respectful of others. This mindset lets us affirm what we are good at while appreciating the talents and values others bring, even when they surpass our own.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Hard stretches are profound teachers',
        text: "When we face tragedies, adversities, or victories, we instinctively open ourselves to empathy toward one another. In the wake of an earthquake that rocked Chicago in 1906, people gathered to form a collective strength and rebuild. Dorothy Day, one of the survivors, reflected in her memoir that while the crisis lasted, people loved each other. In the wake of tragedy, people become equal, and religious or material differences lose their meaning.\n\nNatural disasters, wars, and other large-scale catastrophes show how much we need each other and underscore the power of unity.\n\nWe can look more broadly during hard times and not just focus on ourselves. When bad things happen to people around us, it does not matter who gets hurt the most. In such moments, individualism and selfishness take a back seat as we realize how interconnected we are. At that point it is not just about one person but about society. Shared empathy creates a strong effect that lets everyone who suffers know they are not alone. People united by adversity become a healing force, helping recovery and renewal.\n\nWe become humbled by the knowledge that unfortunate events could have happened to us. It allows us to recognize our vulnerability and teaches us to be more vigilant to prevent possible threats.\n\nReligion is one of the many ways to attain the humility required to care about the world. As Dorothy Day emphasized, having a role model can be a powerful source of inspiration. For Christians, Jesus Christ's humility, illustrated by his alignment with the common people despite being chosen to deliver God's word, serves as a model.\n\nWe have to learn this lesson to live a happy life together, not putting ourselves above others and remembering our interdependence. At some point, we will need a friend's shoulder to cry on, which means we must be willing to give them ours. It is crucial to make sure we treat others with kindness and respect. We must be ready to show empathy and compassion to those around us and be open to understanding their needs and experiences.\n\nDifficult times teach us that, through mutual help and support, we can preserve our humanity and build a better future.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Painful stretches can fuel real success',
        text: "Some of the most successful people in business struggled in school. The average GPA of self-made billionaires is around a low B.\n\nRecovering from suffering is not like recovering from a disease. Many people do not come out healed. They come out different, as David Brooks has written.\n\nSometimes, the decision to succeed comes from difficult memories of being rejected or ignored. Formal education was challenging for George Catlett Marshall when he was a teenager. He struggled to speak in front of the class and earned low grades. Despite these struggles, he went on to become a war hero, a former Secretary of State, and a Nobel Prize laureate. What changed George was not formal education or long advice from his parents. What inspired him was a private conversation he accidentally overheard.\n\nGeorge wanted to join the Virginia Military Institute, or VMI, with his brother, but on a fateful day he overheard his brother telling their mother not to let him go. His brother explained that George would disgrace the family name and make things harder for them in their trying times. At that moment, George decided to prove his brother wrong and show that he was not as useless as they thought.\n\nThe VMI gave George a dream and a goal to become a hero, and he did his best to live up to it. He had a clear vision of what he wanted to become and relentlessly pursued it.\n\nSometimes our greatest moments come from painful situations, but we can use them as inspiration to become better people. Instead of dwelling on the negative, we can look for the positive lesson in a hard experience. We can use our struggles to grow stronger and wiser.\n\nThere is no limit to what we can achieve if we put our minds to it.\n\nIt is not enough to have a conviction. We have to do what it takes to succeed. George Catlett Marshall's example shows that goal motivation can take different forms. Even if we are the only person who believes in our success at first, things can work out, and we can change others' opinions about our capabilities and talents.\n\nFor reference, Albert Einstein, one of the most famous figures in science, dropped out of school at 15 because of academic challenges.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Sometimes love can feel suffocating',
        text: "Nearly everyone yearns for love, because it makes us feel meaningful and necessary. While it is true that love and attention are essential, we should not demand them at the expense of others. We often get too selfish with our desire for attention, making things difficult for the people around us. Life is about compromise, because people will not always share the same views on every issue.\n\nBalancing another person's view with our own makes reaching agreement on many things easier.\n\nMary Anne was born into a devoted Christian family at a time when religious ideas were starting to lose ground to scientific facts. She was separated from her mother, who was ill during her childhood, and sent to a boarding school as a little girl. Her family called Anne back home to care for her mother and siblings when her mother became ill with breast cancer some years later.\n\nGrowing up, she lacked the motherly love she deserved, and her brother, whom she tried to form a bond with, soon grew tired of her and moved on with his life. The lack of affection at a tender age meant Anne craved attention. Desperate to fill the void left by her mother, who died from cancer, Anne devoted her life to Christianity. Her religious belief tipped toward near extremism because she became too obsessed with being religious. Her spiritual focus affected everyone around her, and she had trouble making friends until she realized she was overdoing it. She saw that her devotion to Christianity came from wanting others to see her as a saint and give her the attention she craved. Her need for love had clouded her judgment, and she quickly adjusted.\n\nLove requires accepting people for who they are without intending to change them.\n\nAlthough we all crave love and attention, we have to be careful not to overburden others with our care. True love means respecting others' rights to their space and giving them as much attention as they need. It is also about not being selfish and hearing other people's desires. We should always find a balance between showing care and respecting the freedom of others.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Do not let life’s complexity lead you off course',
        text: "Even Samuel Johnson, renowned for his intellectual contributions, endured a rough childhood that shaped his life. His father was an unprofitable bookseller, and his mother was uneducated. Their marriage was unhappy since they had no common interests. During his infant years, he went under the care of a wet nurse whose infected milk impaired his cognitive ability. Johnson later caught smallpox, which left him with many wounds and scars. His physical appearance made him feel inferior, and he withdrew from society. He became violent toward others, even when they tried to help. Though he loved socializing, he hated being teased for his disability, so he kept to himself.\n\nFortunately, he caught a streak of good luck when he worked for The Gentleman's Magazine. In 1738, the law prohibited journalists from attending parliamentary meetings and publishing actual stories.\n\nJournalists made speeches based on what they could find or hear and posted them as originals to keep people informed. Johnson was an avid reader when he was young and developed a passion for writing, so he helped the magazine compose speeches. His compositions were so good that wealthy men in parliament adopted them and used them as speeches.\n\nDespite all the difficulties that came his way, Johnson became a prominent essayist. His hard experiences helped him recognize the world's imperfection early on, and he skillfully wove this knowledge into his pieces. Johnson managed to keep his compassion, empathy, and understanding of others. Thanks to his extreme sensitivity and even vulnerability, he could notice things often overlooked by most and share his discoveries. Skepticism, doubt, and deep reflection on life helped him see that he is no more imperfect than anyone else.\n\nSometimes our limitations help us find purpose in life and achieve success.\n\nAlthough there are many moments we cannot influence, there is always that part we control. Samuel Johnson realized that his unique background could be the source of his creativity and self-realization. He embraced his struggles with courage and resilience, determined to make the best of his life.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Life is more than pleasure',
        text: "Every day, we try to balance enjoying life and following moral rules. Sometimes it is challenging to deny ourselves what we want and choose what is right instead. We focus on our desires and needs, forgetting that the universe does not revolve around us alone. The journey toward ourselves and inner harmony begins with the understanding that we are not perfect. We all have good and bad qualities, and that is fine. They are just a small part of what makes us human. Even when we err, we can reflect on our actions and learn valuable lessons for the future. We are both weak and strong, passionate and free, and that lets us challenge ourselves. By recognizing our imperfections, we can finally see that they make us unique and allow us to make mistakes and grow. We all have different paths to follow, and we should strive to find our inner balance and strength to live life to the fullest. Accepting our flaws and using them as stepping stones is crucial.\n\nPride limits our open-mindedness and is one of the biggest problems in our lives. It hides our shortcomings, distorts reality, and makes us believe in our superiority over others, slowing our self-improvement.\n\nGetting in touch with your inner self is what builds character.\n\nDeveloping our personality means working against our weaknesses and gradually building new attitudes, aspirations, and habits. If we make disciplined, balanced choices, we can change patterns that have been part of us for years.\n\nWe have to realize that the things that lead us astray, such as lust, fear, vanity, and gluttony, are short-term. On the other hand, a true sense of good character that displays courage, honesty, and humility lasts longer. People who develop positive qualities can build stronger relationships and cope better with life's difficulties. Good character gives us the joy and satisfaction we need for a fulfilling life.\n\nTrue happiness comes freely to those who have mastered the art of staying satisfied.\n\nSound moral values allow us to positively influence the people around us and the world. They help us make the right decisions at critical moments and stay honest with ourselves in any situation.",
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thought',
        text: "Who we are depends not only on the external image we present to the world but also on our internal state and experiences. Without a doubt, creative achievements and success matter, yet our characters mean even more. When we develop our positive moral qualities, we contribute to the good of the entire world. It helps us stay empathetic and understanding in challenging situations and raises our social awareness. The common good depends on our thoughts and actions, so we have to protect their purity and justice.\n\nThe earth needs us as much as we need it. Our primary concern should not be what we stand to gain from our environment. We have to set aside the selfish thought of putting ourselves first and embrace the power of being a community. As humans, we are responsible for each other, and that responsibility is only possible through good traits.\n\nGood character is not entirely innate. It is the collective duty of society to teach ourselves to be better with each passing day. To enjoy a satisfying life, we have to examine ourselves and correct our past mistakes. We should not be too hard on ourselves, because we can only improve our characters with good intentions and by paying attention to our feelings.\n\nTry this. Explore the life principles you follow most often and analyze how they affect your happiness and satisfaction. Start your day with gratitude to the world. It will help you notice more positive things in your life. Meditate when you feel that negative emotions and feelings are overwhelming. Put everything aside and give yourself a few minutes of total focus.\n\nRead it till the end.",
      },
    ],
  },
};
